<TITLE> Tigers 200-1 at tea, Tamim hits maiden Test ton </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 12 (bdnews24.com)  Tamim Iqbal completed a maiden Test century to consolidate Bangladesh's position at tea on the fourth day of the first Test against West Indies at Kingstown, St Vincent on Sunday. The Tigers went into the break on 200-1, a lead of 131. Tamim, who completed a maiden Test century after lunch, was batting on 104 while his partner Junaed Siddique had made 59 not out in a productive session that yielded 118 runs for the unbroken second wicket. The left-handed opener, who was dropped twice either side of lunch, reached the landmark when pushed the ball between point and cover off Ryan Austin with the score on 176-1. Tamim's previous Test best was 84 on debut against New Zealand at Dunedin in 2008 where he also hit back-to-back fifties. Bangladesh scored 238 in their first innings and then dismissed the hosts for
